      <h1>Getting Started with Game Development</h1>
      <p class="meta">Published on January 21, 2026</p>
    </header>

    <p>Game development is an exciting field that combines creativity, technical skills, and problem-solving. Whether you're a complete beginner or have some programming experience, this guide will help you take your first steps into creating games.</p>

    <h2>Why Game Development?</h2>
    <p>Games are a powerful medium for storytelling, education, and entertainment. Learning game development teaches you valuable skills in programming, design, and project management.</p>

    <h2>Essential Tools</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Game Engines:</strong> Unity, Unreal Engine, or Godot</li>
      <li><strong>Programming Languages:</strong> C#, C++, or GDScript</li>
      <li><strong>Art Tools:</strong> Aseprite, Blender, or Photoshop</li>
      <li><strong>Version Control:</strong> Git</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>First Steps</h2>
    <ol>
      <li>Choose a game engine that matches your skill level</li>
      <li>Learn the basics of programming</li>
      <li>Create your first simple game (like Pong or a platformer)</li>
      <li>Join game development communities for support</li>
    </ol>

    <h2>Resources</h2>
    <p>Here are some great resources to continue your learning journey:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><a href="https://unity.com/">Unity Learn</a></li>
      <li><a href="https://godotengine.org/">Godot Documentation</a></li>
      <li><a href="https://www.gamedev.net/">GameDev.net Forums</a></li>
    </ul>

    <p>Remember, the key to success in game development is persistence and continuous learning. Start small, build projects, and don't be afraid to experiment!</p>
